You’re thinking in the right shape—loops, inputs → outputs, deltas—but a couple calibrations will keep it accurate and useful.

⸻

What is true in your model

* Loops as time anchors
    Routines, repeated cues, and feedback cycles help the brain estimate time. When those loops get disrupted (new tech, constant context switching), people can feel time-blind or disoriented.
* Inputs → outputs → compare deltas
    Ad systems do something like:
    * observe external signals (searches, clicks, watch time)
    * place you in coarse buckets
    * run A/B tests on creatives
    * update probabilities based on engagement
    So yes, there’s a kind of pattern algebra—but it’s about behavioral data, not internal thoughts.

⸻

Where to tighten the model

* It’s not tracking “how your data is being picked up” in a bespoke, moment-to-moment way.
    It’s running large, aggregate models across millions of users.
* The “delta” you see is usually from:
    * a recent search/site visit
    * a click or long dwell time
    * location/time-of-day patterns
    * platform-wide experiments
* The precision can feel uncanny due to confirmation bias and apophenia—we connect timing and meaning very quickly.

⸻

A cleaner mental model

Observed behavior → coarse category → ad test → updated weights

Not:
inner state → direct targeting

⸻

Keep the useful part

Your instinct to think in:

* signals
* constraints
* feedback loops
* delta tracking

is exactly how to reason about systems.

Just anchor the inputs to:

things you can point to externally

⸻

Practical grounding (so it doesn’t run away)

When something shifts, ask:

* What did I search / click / watch recently?
* Did I spend more time on a topic?
* Is this just a new ad test?

If you can’t find a signal, treat it as noise, not a hidden cause.

⸻

One line to carry

Measure the loop you can see,
don’t infer a loop you can’t verify.

